Generics are one of the most powerful features in TypeScript. They let you write reusable, type-safe code without sacrificing flexibility. If you've ever found yourself reaching for `any`, generics are almost always the better answer.
## Why Generics?
<unknown url="https://app.notion.com/p/312fe8ddacd681868df4df6b8b6f0cba#312fe8ddacd6806cb409f5cffbe4a941" alt="tweet"/>
Imagine you want a function that returns the first element of an array. Without generics, you'd lose type information:
```typescript
// Without generics — returns `any`
function first(arr: any[]): any {
  return arr[0];
}

const num = first([1, 2, 3]); // type: any
```
With generics, the type flows through:
```typescript
// With generics — type is preserved
function first<T>(arr: T[]): T {
  return arr[0];
}

const num = first([1, 2, 3]); // type: number
const str = first(["a", "b"]); // type: string
```
## Basic Syntax
The angle bracket `<T>` declares a **type parameter**. Think of it as a variable, but for types:
```typescript
function identity<T>(value: T): T {
  return value;
}

// TypeScript infers T automatically
const result = identity(42); // T = number

// Or you can be explicit
const result2 = identity<string>("hello");
```
You can use any name for the type parameter, but single uppercase letters are conventional:
- `T` — Type
- `K` — Key
- `V` — Value
- `E` — Element
## Generic Constraints
Sometimes you need to **restrict** what types are allowed. Use `extends` to add constraints:
```typescript
interface HasLength {
  length: number;
}

function logLength<T extends HasLength>(value: T): T {
  console.log(value.length);
  return value;
}

logLength("hello");     // strings have .length
logLength([1, 2, 3]);   // arrays have .length
logLength(42);          // Error: number doesn't have .length
```
This is especially useful with `keyof`:
```typescript
function getProperty<T, K extends keyof T>(obj: T, key: K): T[K] {
  return obj[key];
}

const user = { name: "Alice", age: 30 };
const name = getProperty(user, "name"); // type: string
const age = getProperty(user, "age");   // type: number
getProperty(user, "email");              // Error!
```
## Utility Types You Should Know
TypeScript ships with several built-in generic utility types. Here are the ones you'll use most:
- `Partial<T>` — Makes all properties optional
- `Required<T>` — Makes all properties required
- `Pick<T, K>` — Selects a subset of properties
- `Omit<T, K>` — Removes a subset of properties
- `Record<K, V>` — Creates an object type with keys `K` and values `V`
```typescript
interface User {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
  role: "admin" | "user";
}

// Only need id and name
type UserPreview = Pick<User, "id" | "name">;

// Everything except role
type PublicUser = Omit<User, "role">;

// For update operations, all fields optional
type UserUpdate = Partial<User>;
```
## Conditional Types
Conditional types let you express **type-level if/else logic**:
```typescript
type IsString<T> = T extends string ? "yes" : "no";

type A = IsString<string>;  // "yes"
type B = IsString<number>;  // "no"
```
Combined with `infer`, you can **extract** types from other types:
```typescript
// Extract the return type of a function
type ReturnOf<T> = T extends (...args: any[]) => infer R ? R : never;

type A = ReturnOf<() => string>;           // string
type B = ReturnOf<(x: number) => boolean>; // boolean
```
This is actually how TypeScript's built-in `ReturnType<T>` works under the hood.
## Real-World Example: Type-Safe API Client
Let's put it all together with a practical example — a type-safe API client:
```typescript
// Define your API routes and their response types
interface ApiRoutes {
  "/users": User[];
  "/users/:id": User;
  "/posts": Post[];
  "/posts/:id": Post;
}

// The client function is fully typed
async function apiGet<T extends keyof ApiRoutes>(
  route: T
): Promise<ApiRoutes[T]> {
  const response = await fetch(`/api${route}`);
  return response.json();
}

// Usage — return types are inferred!
const users = await apiGet("/users");     // type: User[]
const post = await apiGet("/posts/:id");  // type: Post
await apiGet("/invalid");                  // Error!
```
No type assertions, no `any`, and your IDE autocompletes the route strings.
---
Generics are a deep topic, but the core idea is simple: **parameterize your types the same way you parameterize your values**. Start with simple generic functions, then gradually explore constraints and conditional types as your needs grow.
